                    <history>
                        <origin> Completed by <persName role="scr" key="person_f6908">Kīkah b.
                                Mihrjī b. Rānān b. Chāndā</persName>, probably in <origPlace
                                cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001592"
                                >Surat</origPlace>
                            <origDate calendar="other" when="1660-03-22">day of <hi rend="italic"
                                    >Rām</hi> (12) month of <hi rend="italic">Amurdād</hi> 1029 AY
                                (22 March 1660 CE), equal to Samvat 1717 VS (as written in Gujarati
                                to the left)</origDate>.</origin>
                        <provenance><p>Probably acquired by <persName role="fmo"
                                    ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/49590078/" key="person_49590078"
                                    >Samuel Guise (1751–1811)</persName> in <placeName type="city"
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001592">Surat</placeName>
                                where he served as a surgeon until <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                    when="1795">1795</date>, possibly from the widow of <persName
                                    role="fmo" cert="high">Dastūr Darab (d. 1772)</persName>, Parsi
                                preceptor of Indologist <persName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/29529168">M. Anquetil du
                                    Perron</persName> between 1758 to 1760. Listed for sale in the
                                second <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1793">1793</date> of
                                Guise's collection, p. 29, no. 354. Since Guise omits this
                                manuscript in his first catalogue published in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1792">1792</date>, but
                                    <persName>William Ouseley</persName> notes the title in his
                                    <title>Oriental Collections</title> in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1798">1798</date>, Guise likely
                                acquired it after he returned to India.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>Subsequently sold by <orgName role="auc"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134139493" key="person_134139493"
                                    >Leigh and Sotheby</orgName>, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                                    key="place_7011781">London</placeName>, on <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1812-07-03">3 July 1812</date>,
                                where <placeName>Manchester</placeName> librarian <persName
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/92189357" key="person_92189357">John
                                    Haddon Hindley (1765–1827)</persName> purchased it for 3
                                shillings and sixpence.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p>After Hindley's death, <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                                    key="place_7011781">London</placeName> antiquarian dealers
                                    <orgName role="bsl"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/1555163159917201640001"
                                    key="person_1555163159917201640001"><persName
                                        key="person_1555163159917201640001" role="bsl"
                                        change="#prov-markup">Howell and
                                    Stewart</persName></orgName> offered it for sale, from whom
                                legal clerk <persName role="fmo" key="person_f3620">Samuel Hawtayne
                                    Lewin (1795-1840)</persName> probably purchased it in <date
                                    calendar="#Gregorian" when="1828-02">Feb. 1828</date> as per his
                                pencilled note on folio <locus from="1a" to="1a"
                            >1a</locus>.</p></provenance>
                        <provenance><p> Subsequently acquired by Persian scholar <persName
                                    type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                                    key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName>,
                                after whose death <placeName
                                    ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                                    key="place_7011781">London</placeName> antiquarian dealer
                                    <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard
                                    Quaritch (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to
                                    <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                                    >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName>
                                in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866">1866</date>.
                            </p></provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
                                    change="#prov-markup" key="person_f6379">Enriqueta Rylands
                                    (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                    when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard"
                                    role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                                    key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                    Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" role="dnr"
